  "text": "Evidence directly relating to workplaces and employees is still fairly limited, but there is sociological research on specific practices that offers insights into self-tracking employees and employment cultures. Not all are unequivocally positive. [CITATION_1] , for instance, expressed concern about the tensions between playful gamification and more serious surveillance, and the social effects of making \"weight loss, workplace productivity, educational advancement, [and] consumer loyalty\" (p. 163) seem like a game. She discussed the workplace examples of call center and hi-tech work redesign, with the crucial concern that the work-play contradiction \"kills the motivation to play and instead motivates workers to thwart and resist the systems that have attempted to mislead them and take advantage of their playful tendencies\" (Whitson 2013, p. 174) .",
